      <link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/08/books/philip-caputo-dead.html</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/08/books/philip-caputo-dead.html</guid>
      <atom:link href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/08/books/philip-caputo-dead.html" rel="standout"></atom:link>
      <description>“A Rumor of War,” about his service as a Marine Corps infantry officer and published in 1977, relentlessly detailed “the things men do in war and the things war does to them.”</description>
      <dc:creator>Joseph Berger</dc:creator>
      <pubDate>Fri, 08 May 2026 13:55:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_per">Caputo, Philip</category>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/des">Deaths (Obituaries)</category>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/des">Vietnam War</category>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/des">United States Defense and Military Forces</category>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/des">Books and Literature</category>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/des">News and News Media</category>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_ttl">A Rumor of War (Book)</category>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_org">Chicago Tribune</category>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_org">United States Marine Corps</category>
      <category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_geo">Vietnam</category>
      <media:content height="1800" medium="image" url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/05/10/obituaries/08caputo-top-print1/08caputo-top-mediumSquareAt3X-v2.jpg" width="1800"></media:content>
      <media:credit>Frank Lennon/Toronto Star, via Getty Images</media:credit>
      <media:description>Philip Caputo in 1987. “To call it the best book about Vietnam is to trivialize it,” the novelist and screenwriter John Gregory Dunne wrote in his review of “A Rumor of War.” “Heartbreaking, terrifying and enraging, it belongs to the literature of men at arms.”</media:description>
    </item>
